asr.scoring_recipe:
Use a Mixed Error Rate (MER): tokenize each CJK character as one token and each contiguous English/alphanumeric run as one word token, then compute Levenshtein WER over those tokens (= CER on Chinese, WER on English, unified). This is the standard zh+en eval (WenetSpeech/ESPnet style). Library: jiwer (jiwer.wer on space-joined token strings). Normalization pipeline, applied IDENTICALLY to reference and hypothesis BEFORE scoring: 1) unicodedata.normalize('NFKC', t) — folds full-width to half-width (digits, latin, punctuation) and removes most width ambiguity; 2) OpenCC script unification — convert BOTH ref and hyp to one script (pick one direction and stick to it, e.g. OpenCC('t2s') to compare in Simplified, or keep Taiwan style with 's2twp'); this is REQUIRED because the model may emit Simplified for zh-TW audio and would otherwise be penalized; 3) English lowercasing t.lower(); 4) strip punctuation (CJK 。，、！？；：「」『』（）《》… and ASCII .,!?;:'"-()[] ) and collapse whitespace; remove spaces between CJK chars; 5) Number handling: NFKC already unifies width; ASR output and TTS reference may disagree digit-vs-spelled ("3"/"三"/"three"), so EITHER normalize both to a canonical form with a lib like cn2an / num2words, OR document that numbers are scored as-written — pick one and report it. Sketch:

  import re, unicodedata, jiwer
  from opencc import OpenCC
  cc = OpenCC('t2s')                      # unify script for BOTH ref & hyp
  PUNCT = re.compile(r"[，。！？、；：「」『』（）()\[\]{}《》〈〉…—\-~·.,!?;:\"'`]")
  CJK   = re.compile(r"[\u3400-\u4dbf\u4e00-\u9fff]")
  def norm(t):
      t = unicodedata.normalize('NFKC', t); t = cc.convert(t); t = t.lower()
      t = PUNCT.sub('', t); return re.sub(r"\s+", ' ', t).strip()
  def tok(t):
      out=[]
      for w in t.split():
          i=0
          while i<len(w):
              if CJK.match(w[i]): out.append(w[i]); i+=1
              else:
                  j=i
                  while j<len(w) and not CJK.match(w[j]): j+=1
                  out.append(w[i:j]); i=j
      return out
  def mer(ref, hyp):
      return jiwer.wer(' '.join(tok(norm(ref))), ' '.join(tok(norm(hyp))))

Report MER overall, and optionally pure CER (Chinese chars only) and WER (English words only) as a breakdown. For TTS intelligibility, MER between the TTS input text and the ASR transcript = lower is better.
